For the poached pears, place the pears upright in a large saucepan. Cover with the wine, brandy, 500ml/18fl oz water and the sugar. Add the cinnamon, vanilla pods, the rest of the spices and the citrus zest.Bring to the boil, stir the poaching liquor gently and skim off any residue from the surface. Cover with a cartouche (a circle of baking paper sat on the surface of the liquid) and simmer for 10 minutes. Remove from the heat and leave to cool.Transfer the cooled pears to a deep dish and cover with half the liquid. Boil the rest of the liquid in the saucepan until the volume of liquid has reduced to a syrup. Strain and set aside.For the custard, heat the milk, cream and vanilla in a heavy-based saucepan until almost boiling.In a mixing bowl, beat the egg yolks, sugar, flour and cornflour until white and smooth. Pour the warm milk mixture over the egg mixture and beat well until incorporated. Pour back into the saucepan and bring to a simmer, stirring all the time. As soon as the custard has started to bubble, remove from the heat and remove the vanilla pods.To serve, place a poached pear in each serving bowl. Pour the custard into the bottom of the bowls and glaze the pears with the poaching syrup.